<br>
From the first post in this thread:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Mitigation AC should just determine the distribution of hits over the twenty different X values. The distribution would just be a probability for each X value, based on mitigation AC and the mob's attack rating in some way.<br>
<br>
For a tank with high mitigation AC, the probabilities would be skewed such that, generally, there is a higher probability of being hit for a lower X value than a higher X value.<br>
<br>
And it should also be noted that it is possible to mitigate hits into misses. Go tank a decaying skeleton and you'll see that this is true (you have high mitigation AC, it has a low attack rating).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I want to address the last paragraph. I have still not seen any concrete data that consistently shows that a HIT is being mitigated down to 0 damage and therefore a MISS. The example that is used with the Decaying Skeleton could just as simply be that the Avoidance AC of the Player is so much higher than the Skellie that actual misses occur. While the hypothesis that HITs can be mitigated to MISSes is a possible one no proof has been presented nor I believe is it possible to be presented from our view of the game engine.<br>
<br>
IMO it is not likely that this hypothesis is the case. We know that damage = DB + [DI *x] (where x is an integer from 1 to 20). Which gives a MIN of DB + DI and a MAX of DB + 20DI. For the damage then to be mitigated down to 0 would mean that the formula DB + [DI *x] is at some point totally disregarded, I could suppose that this might be coded to be the case if x is &lt; -100 or some other low cutoff figure but it seems strange from a coding point of view to do this. Still, not impossible but to my reasoning unlikely.<br>
<br>
I think the idea of HITs being mitigated to MISSes was a hypothesis created at some point to describe a certain set of data values and it was embraced by a few who thought it sounds interesting. As of yet I have not seen any real proof for it although as always I am open to to it.<br>
<br>
-----<br>
<br>
The excerpt by Thresher in the first post I almost totally agree with.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
The first post presented by Gjin LoL (wthin the condensation by Tugurok if I recall correctly, was not embraced by too many others in that thread. Hard to recall as it was a long time ago, but I do remember it from back then and I also remember opposing it personally.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Lets assume that Z = (1 - AC/Atk).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Again this was a possible explanation but never demonstrated to fit any relevant sample data. I also remeber presenting the idea that instead of AC being related to ATK as a function of divsion it might be closer to a function of subtraction. No progress was made towards finding a suitable formula IIRC. The most useful part of that post was simply that the distributive values for the variable x are likely to be a function of AC, ATK and possibly the levels of the two parties.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
In the second post where Gjin LoL presnts his proof he assumes that Cazic Thule has a ATK value of 2000. He then uses his own hypothesis to prove that to jump from a modal to the next modal that it requires an extra 100 AC each time. I am not sure if he really understood that using the numbers he orignally assumed all that he proved was that 2000 / 20 = 100. I will elaborate:<br>
<br>
He started with<br>
(1 - AC/2000)*20 = x<br>
<br>
which can be shown also as<br>
20 - AC/100 = x<br>
<br>
or<br>
20 - x = AC/100<br>
2000 - 100x = AC<br>
<br>
Now, since x is a integer value from 1 to 20<br>
MIN DMG: 2000 - 100 = AC<br>
MIN DMG: AC = 1900<br>
<br>
MAX DMG: 2000 - 2000 = AC<br>
MAX DMG: AC = 0<br>
<br>
And every step between the min and max damage modal is in increments of 100 AC. If a different number than 2000 ATK had been assumed then his conclusion of 100 AC increments would not have eventuated. Lucky guess on the numbers I guess but all he proves is 2000 / 20 = 100.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
Kryai's post is quite a accurate and concise explanation of some details that we know so far except for what I point out in my next paragraph. Only problem was he listed the DB of Emperor Ssraeshza as 250.3. Asky did correct him 3 posts later though but without referring directly to his error.<br>
<br>
Kyrai made a slight error here:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> #3 PC and NPC damage is calculated differently. I should NEVER hit for 1 damage if using this formula. I've never seen Emperor hit anyone for 1 damage. PC damage then has to take a further thing into consideration (MOB AC perhaps)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->When you are hitting with your main hand hand you never hit for 1 if you are a level 60. You hit for a minimum of 11 + (Damage_rating / 10). For Reference the acronym DB comes from Damage Bonus, the DB for any PC weapon is the listed Damage bonus if in main hand and is 0 if in offhand. Also DI for a PC weapon is the damage rating listed on a weapon divided by 10.<br>
<br>
Zebedi points this out in a later post:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I did some testing, and you actually will never hit for less than 12 damage with your main hand.<br>
<br>
It's off hand hits that can be 1.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Tugurok later responds to Zebedi with:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Zebedi, as far as I know that is not news because 60 warriors have a level damage bonus of 11.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Hopefully now Tugurok sees why Zebedi was making that statement, he was correcting Kryai. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
Sashanna writes:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> erm has anyone found a link between a mob's attack and its DI?<br>
<br>
secondly, anyone found if debuffing a mob's attack affects its DI? this might be the x factor that affects the DI skew.<br>
<br>
if there was a way to skew DI downwards this would increase the effectiveness of evasive... <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I don't think that a mob's ATK would be linked to its DI, when a mob is debuffed its DI does not decrease although its ATK is affected (assuming mobs have an ATK rating like us).<br>
<br>
What you might be trying to say though is: Is there a correlation between a mob's ATK and the distribution of x? This is quite likely, ie you may be able to reduce the AVG or modal hit of a mob by reducing its ATK.<br>
<br>
Would reducing the AVG or modal hit of a mob (by reducing its ATK) make evasive more effective? Perhap, but it would have to be a massive debuff to the mobs ATK value to do so. It can be tested but the results will probably not show a large difference except for mobs that are near the borderline anyway.<br>
<br>
