Stizok wrote:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1) u can avoid hits completely<br>
2) u take max damage more often than all other values (against uber mobs)<br>
now, u assumed there is a formula that calculates a value X from 1 to 20 which will add a damage interval to a defined base damage. X depends on AC of tank, level of tank, class of tank, attack of mob and level of mob. not that i could tell for sure, but i assume verants formula first calculates a value from negative infinity to positive infinity, after that the numbers smaller than 0 become 0 (0 means miss) and all the numbers larger than 20 become 20 (20 means max hit) and all the numbers between 0 and 20 are rounded to the next integer. this would explain why<br>
1) a decaded skeleton misses a high level so often (many negative numbers, thus rounded up to 0) or why<br>
2) uber mobs hit often for max damage (many numbers larger than 20 and thus rounded down to 20).<br>
verants formula will most likely stay a secret forever.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Your first point says that you can avoid hits completely but since this whole thread is about the mitigation side of damage i would assume that you meant to say that HITs can be mitigated into MISSes. I do not acknowledge this still and would appreciate any data, parses or proofs available on the subject.<br>
<br>
The place in your post where you say &quot;numbers smaller than 0 become 0 (0 means miss)&quot;. I would porpose (like others before me in this thread) that numbers smaller than 1 become 1 (1 means a MIN hit). I find no grounds to support the usage of a 0 value for x becoming a MISS, if x could equal x then we would be more likely to see a MIN hit of DB (instead of DB + DI) rather than it being mitigated cmpletely to a MISS.<br>
<br>
The reason a decayed skeleton misses so often is because you have very high avoidance ability in relations to its ability to hit you. IE MISSes are completely natural and computed before any type of damage or x value is considered. If a MISS is registered there is no reason to calculate x.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
NoOneOfNote makes an interesting point. With testing of varying levels of AC against mobs of the same level it could be tracked whether the modal does move after a certain amount of AC. Rather than just tracking total or AVG damage taken, tracking where the modal (or second modal) falls will give a much more detailed way of guaging the real effiency of AC.<br>
<br>
----<br>
<br>
Crayno, in your post about the Statue fight I think you forgot to take out any values of a defensive warrior.<br>
<br>
From your data I would have to guess that the real MIN hit for crush was actually 245. This would give the Statue DB = 200 and DI = 45. Making the MAX = 1100 and MIN = 245. Under defensive the MAX = 650 and MIN = 222.<br>
<br>
Note that if you use (from the values I give above) the non-defensive MAX and the Defensive MIN you would get the values that you assumed were a non-defensive MAX and MIN data set.<br>
<br>
Also you wrote: &quot;DB=Min hit+DI =201+47.3=248.3&quot;<br>
<br>
Note that the formula for calculating DB is (MIN - DI) not (MIN + DI). As a general check for you next time, the DB can never be greater than the MIN hit.<br>
<br>
